    {
      "turn_number": 24,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "My husband was there — bless him. He’d worked a double the day before and still managed to get to the hospital on time, pale and shaky, clutching my hand like he was holding the world together. I remember his thumb rubbing circles on my palm; it kept me from hyperventilating. No family could come — we’re new here and everyone’s hours away — and that absence felt huge in the delivery room, a quiet hole I kept noticing between contractions.\n\nA midwife named Lena was my rock. She had a calm voice and kept explaining things in plain words, not the shorthand some of the residents used. There were nurses coming and going, one of them — Maria — stayed long enough to braid my hair back and whisper that I was doing great. The OB came in when they needed to make decisions; she was efficient, sometimes brusque, but steady.\n\nI missed having my mom. I kept looking at my husband and the midwife like they were the whole world. Their presence — practical, tender, sometimes weary — made the difference between feeling alone and feeling held.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "V1_BIRTH_Q04",
      "input_tokens": 1159,
      "output_tokens": 486
    },
